  "text": "In rodents, working memory has classically been synonymous with short-term spatial or visual-spatial memory [CITATION_1] and delay-dependent tasks have been suggested as a way of assessing this domain in mice [CITATION_2] . In this study, we employed the delayed alternation variant of the Y maze task [CITATION_3] . All mice learned to complete the spatial discrimination task with a 90% criterion level of alternation within the 7 day training session with no overall difference in performance between genotypes (Fig. 1a , genotype effect, F 1, 22 = 1.03, p = 0.322). Further, Brd1 +/À and WT mice displayed similar levels of alternation when choice runs followed immediately after information runs, but when a 90 s delay was introduced, Brd1 +/À mice displayed significantly less alternation than WT mice (Figs. 1b and S1, genotype effect, F 1.36 = 6.438 , p = 0.016).",
